Thanks for reviving this PR, @reedsa! 

@e3243eric I made a comment around the messaging in the `DeprecatedMethod` class, let me know what you think. I'm happy to make that update if you don't want/have time to, just let me know!

Thanks for taking it on!

I really like the idea of spinning off the visualization functionality to a separate module; I 100% agree some of our modules are getting long enough to be unwieldy. I also think the plan was cleanly executed here and can get behind merging it.

However, I want to step back for one minute and think whether there is an even better way to set up the architecture.

In my understanding, modules are for grouping related classes and methods, and classes are for grouping related methods and data. So when I look at the Visualization class I get a yellow flag when I see that it only has one piece of data and the vast majority of its methods are `@staticmethod`.

To me, it would make more sense to leave all the stuff in `visualization.py` as functions (e.g. which take as a first argument an `Atoms` instance where necessary), and then *bind* the relevant methods to the `Atoms` class at instantiation.

Below is a toy example of what I mean. For a user who has instantiated an `Atoms` object, it will look identical, but there are changes behind the scenes. In my opinion this alternative setup is shorter, cleaner, and makes more sense organizationally, but I'm actively soliciting a rebuttal here to see if anyone smells any problems!

```python
# Current
## Visualization module
class Visualization:
    def __init__(self, structure):
        self.ref_structure = structure
        
    def plotA(self):
        """PlotA docstring"""
        self._subroutine("Plotting {} in A way".format(self.ref_structure))
        
    def plotB(self):
        """PlotB docstring"""
        self._subroutine("Plotting {} in A way".format(self.ref_structure))
        
    @staticmethod
    def _subroutine(msg):
        print(msg)

## Atoms module
class Atoms:
    def __init__(self):
        self.visualization = Visualization(self)
        
    def plotA(self):
        self.visualization.plotA()
    plotA.__doc__ = Visualization.plotA.__doc__
    
    def plotB(self):
        self.visualization.plotA()
    plotB.__doc__ = Visualization.plotB.__doc__
    
    def __repr__(self):
        return "I'm a structure"
```

```python
# Operationally equivalent alternative
## Visualization module
def plotA(atoms):
    """PlotA docstring"""
    _subroutine("Plotting {} in A way".format(atoms))

def plotB(atoms):
    """PlotB docstring"""
    _subroutine("Plotting {} in A way".format(atoms))

def _subroutine(msg):
    print(msg)
  
## Atoms module
from types import MethodType
class Atoms:
    def __init__(self):
        self.plotA = MethodType(plotA, self)
        self.plotB = MethodType(plotB, self)
        
    def __repr__(self):
        return "I'm a structure"
```

The only thing I can see is that if you were trying to look at the docstrings from the class level (`Atoms.plotA?` as opposed to `atoms_instance.plotA?`) you'd run into trouble. But I don't think I've ever done this in a notebook. If it's a sufficiently rare behaviour, then the shortcoming is not important.

Thanks for the proposal and for fixing the documentation!

I checked the various packages you mentioned and can confirm that `weights` (with an `s`) is used across many of them. Thanks for listing those out!

> this is not a breaking change since existing code using `weight` would still work under this PR

@StrikerRUS I noticed you changed the label on this PR to "breaking". I'm going to change it back to "feature". As @david-cortes is alluding to, R allows for partial matching of keyword argument names.

```r
f <- function(weights){
    print(weights + 5)
}

f(weight = 7)
# 12
```

@david-cortes will you please add a unit test confirming that weighted training with  `lightgbm::lightgbm()` works as expected using both keyword argument `weight`  and `weights`? As a general rule, every user-facing change to this project should be accompanied by tests demonstrating their correctness and ensuring that we don't accidentally break that behavior with future.

I recall that previously, `R CMD check` complained about the use of partial argument-matching in package code (#3629). If it complains about such a unit test, then I wouldn't support changing this keyword argument. But if it's possible to keep a test demonstrating that both `weight` and `weights` work, then I support this change to make `lightgbm::lightgbm()` a bit more consistent with other statistical modeling packages in R.

